\s1 Daniel Praises God and Interprets the King’s Dream
\m 
\v 24 ⸤Therefore⸥\f + \fr 2:24 \ft Literally “Now because this” \f* Daniel went to Arioch, whom the king had appointed\f + \fr 2:24 \ft Aramaic “has appointed” \f* to destroy the wise men of Babylon; he went and thus he said to him: “You must not destroy the wise men of Babylon; take me in before the king and I will give the explanation\f + \fr 2:24 \ft Or “interpretation” \f* to the king.”
\p 
\v 25 Then Arioch ⸤quickly⸥\f + \fr 2:25 \ft Literally “in haste” \f* brought Daniel in before the king and thus he said to him: “I have found a man among ⸤the exiles⸥\f + \fr 2:25 \ft Literally “the children of exiles” \f* of Judah\f + \fr 2:25 \ft Aramaic “Jehud” \f* who ⸤can relate⸥\f + \fr 2:25 \ft Literally “he will make known” \f* the explanation\f + \fr 2:25 \ft Or “interpretation” \f* to the king. 
\v 26 ⸤The king then asked⸥\f + \fr 2:26 \ft Literally “The king answered” \f* and said to Daniel, whose name \add was\add* Belteshazzar, “Are you able to make known to me the dream that I have seen and its explanation?”\f + \fr 2:26 \ft Or “interpretation” \f* 
\v 27 Daniel answered the king and said, “The mystery that the king asks, no wise men, conjurers,\f + \fr 2:27 \ft Or “enchanters” \f* magicians,\f + \fr 2:27 \ft Or “soothsayer-priests” \f* \add or\add* diviners are able to make known to the king. 
\v 28 But there is a God in heaven \add who\add* reveals mysteries, and he has made known to King Nebuchadnezzar what \add it is\add* that will be at the end of days. This \add is\add* your dream and the visions of your head on your bed.
\p 
\v 29 “\add As for you\add*, king,\f + \fr 2:29 \ft Aramaic “the king” \f* your thoughts on your bed ⸤turned to⸥\f + \fr 2:29 \ft Literally “they went up” \f* what \add it was\add* that would be ⸤in the future⸥,\f + \fr 2:29 \ft Literally “after this” \f* and the revealer of mysteries has made known to you what that would be. 
\v 30 And as for me, \add it is\add* not because of wisdom that is in me more than ⸤any other living person⸥\f + \fr 2:30 \ft Literally “all of living beings” \f* \add that\add* this mystery is revealed to me, but ⸤in order that⸥\f + \fr 2:30 \ft Literally “concerning the matter of” \f* the explanation\f + \fr 2:30 \ft Or “interpretation” \f* may be made known to the king and you will ⸤understand⸥\f + \fr 2:30 \ft Literally “know” \f* the thoughts of your ⸤mind⸥.\f + \fr 2:30 \ft Literally “heart” \f*
\p 
\v 31 “You, O king, were looking and, look, there was one great statue. This statue \add was\add* huge and its brilliance extraordinary, standing \add there\add* before you, and its appearance \add was\add* frightening.\f + \fr 2:31 \ft Or “dreadful” \f* 
\v 32 The head of this statue \add was\add* of fine gold, its chest and its arms of silver, its belly and its thighs of bronze, 
\v 33 its legs of iron, its feet, part of them of iron and part of them of clay. 
\v 34 You were looking on ⸤until⸥\f + \fr 2:34 \ft Literally “until that” \f* a stone was chiseled out\f + \fr 2:34 \ft Or “became loose” \f*—that not by hands—and it struck the statue on its feet of iron and clay, and it broke them in pieces. 
\v 35 Then the iron, the clay, the bronze, the silver and the gold ⸤all at once⸥\f + \fr 2:35 \ft Literally “like one” \f* broke into pieces\f + \fr 2:35 \ft Or “were crushed” \f* and they became like chaff from the summer threshing floor, and the wind carried them away and any trace of them could not be found. But the stone that struck the statue became a great mountain and it filled the whole earth.
\p 
\v 36 “This \add was\add* the dream, and \add now\add* we will tell its interpretation to the king. 
\v 37 You, O king, the king of kings, to whom the God of heaven has given the kingdom, the power and the might and the glory, 
\v 38 and \add also\add* ⸤human beings wherever they dwell⸥,\f + \fr 2:38 \ft Literally “and into all that dwell sons of humankind” \f* the animals of the field and the birds\f + \fr 2:38 \ft Aramaic “bird” \f* of heaven\f + \fr 2:38 \ft Or “the sky” \f*—he has given into your hand and made you ruler over all of them—you are the head of gold. 
\v 39 And after you another kingdom inferior to yours will arise, and another third \add kingdom\add* of bronze that will rule over the whole earth. 
\v 40 And \add a\add* fourth kingdom will be strong as iron, \add and\add* ⸤just as⸥\f + \fr 2:40 \ft Literally “all of because” \f* iron crushes and smashes ⸤everything⸥,\f + \fr 2:40 \ft Literally “the whole thing” \f* and as iron shatters all of these \add other metals\add*, \add so\add* it will crush and it will shatter \add these nations\add*. 
\v 41 ⸤And just as⸥\f + \fr 2:41 \ft Literally “And that” \f* you saw the feet and the toes, ⸤partly potter’s clay⸥\f + \fr 2:41 \ft Literally “from them clay of the potter” \f* and ⸤partly iron⸥,\f + \fr 2:41 \ft Literally “from them iron” \f* it will be a divided kingdom; and ⸤some hardness⸥\f + \fr 2:41 \ft Literally “from the hardness” \f* of the iron will be \add in it\add*, ⸤just as⸥\f + \fr 2:41 \ft Literally “all of because that” \f* you have seen the iron mixed with the wet clay. 
\v 42 And \add as\add* the toes of the feet \add were\add* partly iron and partly clay, \add so\add* part of the kingdom will be strong ⸤and partly brittle⸥.\f + \fr 2:42 \ft Literally “and from it, it will be brittle” \f* 
\v 43 And \add in\add* that you saw the iron was mixed with wet clay, \add so\add* ⸤they will mix in marriage⸥\f + \fr 2:43 \ft Literally “mixing they will in the seed of man” \f* and they will not cling ⸤to one another⸥,\f + \fr 2:43 \ft Literally “this one with that one” \f* just as iron \add does\add* not mix with clay. 
\v 44 And ⸤in the day of those kings⸥,\f + \fr 2:44 \ft Literally “in their days of those kings” \f* the God of heaven will set up a kingdom that will ⸤never⸥\f + \fr 2:44 \ft Literally “to forever not” \f* be destroyed, and the kingdom will not be left for another nation,\f + \fr 2:44 \ft Or “people” \f* and it will bring an end to all these kingdoms, but it will stand ⸤forever⸥.\f + \fr 2:44 \ft Literally “to eternity” \f* 
\v 45 ⸤Inasmuch as⸥\f + \fr 2:45 \ft Literally “All of because that” \f* you saw that a stone from the mountain was chiseled out\f + \fr 2:45 \ft Or “became loose” \f* \add but\add* not by hands, and \add that\add* it crushed the iron, the bronze, the clay, the silver and the gold, \add thereby\add* the great God made known to the king what will be ⸤in the future⸥,\f + \fr 2:45 \ft Literally “after this” \f* and the dream is certain and its explanation trustworthy.”
\s1 The King’s Response to Daniel and His God
\m 
\v 46 Then the king, Nebuchadnezzar, fell on his face and he paid homage to Daniel; and he commanded \add them\add* to offer \add a\add* grain offering and incense offering to him. 
\v 47 The king answered Daniel and said, “⸤Truly⸥\f + \fr 2:47 \ft Literally “From truth that” \f* your God \add is\add* the God of gods and the Lord of kings, and he reveals mysteries, for you are able to reveal this mystery.” 
\v 48 Then the king promoted Daniel and gave him many great gifts, and made him ruler over the whole province of Babylon and the chief prefect over all the wise men of Babylon. 
\v 49 And Daniel made a request from the king, and he appointed Shadrach, Meshach and Abednego over the affairs of the province of Babylon, while Daniel \add remained\add* in the court of the king.
\c 3
\s1 The Faithfulness of Three Young Israelites and God’s Deliverance
\m 
\v 1 Nebuchadnezzar the king made a statue of gold. Its height \add was\add* sixty cubits \add and\add* its width \add was\add* six cubits; he set it up in the valley of Dura in the province of Babylon. 
\v 2 Then Nebuchadnezzar the king sent \add directions\add* to assemble the satraps, the prefects, and the governors, the counselors, the treasurers, the judges, the magistrates and all of the officials of the provinces to come to the dedication of the statue that Nebuchadnezzar the king \add had\add* set up. 
\v 3 Then the satraps, the prefects, the governors, the counselors, the treasurers, the judges, the magistrates, and all the officials of the province \add were\add* assembled for the dedication of the statue that Nebuchadnezzar the king \add had\add* set up, and \add were\add* standing ⸤before⸥\f + \fr 3:3 \ft Literally “to \fq the \ft front” \f* the statue that Nebuchadnezzar had set up. 
\v 4 Then the herald proclaimed ⸤aloud⸥,\f + \fr 3:4 \ft Literally “with power” \f* “To you ⸤it is commanded⸥,\f + \fr 3:4 \ft Literally “they \fq are \ft saying” \f* O peoples, ⸤nations and people of all languages⸥,\f + \fr 3:4 \ft Literally “the nations and the languages” \f* 
\v 5 \add that\add* at the time that you hear the sound of the horn, the flute, \add the\add* lyre, \add the\add* trigon, \add the\add* harp, \add the\add* drum and all kinds of music, you must fall down and you must worship the statue of gold\f + \fr 3:5 \ft Aramaic “the gold” \f* that Nebuchadnezzar the king \add has\add* set up. 
\v 6 And ⸤whoever⸥\f + \fr 3:6 \ft Literally “who that” \f* does not fall down and worship will be thrown ⸤immediately⸥\f + \fr 3:6 \ft Literally “the time” \f* into the midst of the furnace of blazing fire.” 
\v 7 ⸤Therefore⸥,\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Literally “All of because this” \f* ⸤at that time⸥,\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Literally “at the time” \f* ⸤as soon as⸥\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Literally “as that” \f* all the peoples heard the sound of the horn, the flute, \add the\add* lyre, \add the\add* trigon, \add the\add* harp and all kinds of music, all the peoples, ⸤the nations and people of all languages⸥\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Literally “the nations and the languages” \f* \add were\add* falling down \add and\add* were worshiping the statue of gold\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Aramaic “the gold” \f* that Nebuchadnezzar the king had set up.
\p 
\v 8 ⸤Therefore⸥\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Literally “All because of this” \f* ⸤at this time⸥\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Literally “at it the time” \f* \add some\add* ⸤astrologers⸥\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Literally “Chaldean men” \f* came forward and ⸤they denounced the Jews⸥.\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Literally “they ate their pieces of the Jews” \f* 
\v 9 ⸤They responded and said⸥\f + \fr 3:9 \ft Literally “they answered and \fq were \ft saying” \f* to Nebuchadnezzar the king, “O king, may \add you\add* live ⸤forever⸥!\f + \fr 3:9 \ft Literally “to eternity” \f* 
\v 10 You, O king, have made a decree that ⸤everyone⸥\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Literally “all of humanity” \f* who hears the sound of the horn, the flute, \add the\add* lyre, \add the\add* trigon, \add the\add* harp and \add the\add* drum and all kinds of music, he shall fall down and shall worship the statue of gold.\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Aramaic “the gold” \f* 
\v 11 ⸤And whoever⸥\f + \fr 3:11 \ft Literally “And who that” \f* ⸤does not fall down⸥\f + \fr 3:11 \ft Literally “not he falls down” \f* and worship shall be thrown into the midst of the furnace of blazing fire. 
